Phase one: Preprocessing¶

Here we delete files which are not .jpg in both train and test folders (we have files which are .JPG , .jpeg or .gif). Then we iterate over all files and save their address in a list called imgPaths. We also save the categories of images in a list called imgCategs. At the end we make a dataframe called imgPathDf which contains paths of images and thier categories.

In [10]:
imgCategsCounts = {
     "elk": 0,
     "bald_eagle": 0,
     "raven": 0,
     "racoon": 0
}

for imgCateg in imgCategsCounts.keys():
  for file in [file for file in os.listdir("/tmp/dataset/train/" + str(imgCateg)) if not file.endswith(".jpg")]:
      filePath = os.path.join("/tmp/dataset/train/" + imgCateg, file)
      os.remove(filePath)
  for file in [file for file in os.listdir("/tmp/dataset/test/" + str(imgCateg)) if not file.endswith(".jpg")]:
      filePath = os.path.join("/tmp/dataset/test/" + imgCateg, file)
      os.remove(filePath)

imgPathes = list()
imgCategs = list()

for imgCateg in imgCategsCounts.keys():
  for img in os.listdir('/tmp/dataset/train/' + str(imgCateg)):
    imgPathes.append(os.path.join('/tmp/dataset/train/' + str(imgCateg), img))
    imgCategs.append(imgCateg)
    imgCategsCounts[imgCateg] += 1

for imgCateg in imgCategsCounts.keys():
  print(imgCateg, ' counts: ', imgCategsCounts[imgCateg])
imgPathsDf = pd.DataFrame({
        'imgPathes' : imgPathes,
        'imgCategs' : imgCategs 
    })

In the folloing cell we make our main data frames which are ready for training using some methods like ImageDataGenerator and flow_from_dataframe. These methods also scale the images and set the batch size. Here we split images in train folder into two subset called trainSet and validationSet. Later we will train our model on trainSet and try to optimize it by testing it on validationSet (which is actually our test set of data)

In [16]:
dataGenrator = preprocessing.image.ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale = 1/255.0,
    validation_split = 0.2
)

trainSet = dataGenrator.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe = imgPathsDf, 
    x_col = 'imgPathes', 
    y_col = 'imgCategs', 
    target_size = (100, 100), 
    color_mode = 'grayscale', 
    batch_size = 32, 
    class_mode = 'categorical', 
    subset = 'training', 
    shuffle = True
)

validationSet = dataGenrator.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe = imgPathsDf, 
    x_col = 'imgPathes', 
    y_col = 'imgCategs', 
    target_size = (100, 100), 
    color_mode = 'grayscale', 
    batch_size = 32, 
    class_mode = 'categorical', 
    subset = 'validation', 
    shuffle = True
)

allTrainSet = dataGenrator.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe = imgPathsDf, 
    x_col = 'imgPathes', 
    y_col = 'imgCategs', 
    target_size = (100, 100), 
    color_mode = 'grayscale', 
    batch_size = 32, 
    class_mode = 'categorical', 
    shuffle = False
)

One hot encoding: In the following cell we do one hot encoding on the second column of data frame (on categories).

Using this technique normal sentences can be represented as vectors. This vector is made based on the vocabulary size and the encoding schema. Numerical operations can be performed on this vector form.

Applications of One-hot encoding:

Neural networks can tell us if an input image is of a cat or a dog. Since the neural network only uses numbers, it cant output the words cat or dog. Instead, it uses one-hot encoding to represent is prediction in a semantic manner.

  row[i] = 1
  imgPathsDf['imgCategs'] = imgPathsDf['imgCategs'].replace([list(imgCategsCounts.keys())[i]], str(row))

Phase two: Desiging Neural Network¶

We train our first model with 3 layers, each with 1024, 512 and 4 neurons. The learning rate is 0.01 and activation functions are relu (except for the last layer whish is softmax). After training our model on trainSet we validate it by applying it on the validationSet. The results are as follows.

As we can see later the best model will be this one.

In [20]:
# FIRST MODEL

input = layers.Input(shape = (100, 100, 1))
output = layers.Flatten()(input)
output = layers.Dense(1024, activation = "relu")(output)
output = layers.Dense(512, activation = "relu")(output)
output = layers.Dense(4, activation = "softmax")(output)

model = models.Model(inputs = input, outputs = output)
model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.01), loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = 'accuracy')

model.summary()

history = model.fit(trainSet, validation_data=validationSet, epochs = 10)

Phase three: Classifying Data¶

We choosed the model with three layers and relu activation function.

Part One: Optimizers Impacts¶

What is Momentum?

Momentum takes past gradients into account to smooth out the steps of gradient descent. It can be applied with batch gradient descent, mini-batch gradient descent or stochastic gradient descent.

Why using Momentum?

momentum optimizer is faster and better at optimizing the model. Momentum is an easy and quick way to improve upon standard Stochastic Gradient Descent for optimizing Neural Network models. It also increase accuracy.

--> Testing with Momentum = 0.9:

Does increasing Momentum always help?

No. If we increase Momentum too much it will take more past gradients into account which is not good. Also a large Momentum may cause random behavior and stop the learning process, on the other hand very small values wont cause changes.

Why we use multiple epoch?

We want to get good performance on non-training data (in practice this can be approximated with a hold-out set); usually (but not always) that takes more than one pass over the training data.

Additionally, and independent of any out-of-sample considerations, it's typical that gradient descent doesn't reach a (global or local) minimum after the first epoch. For any problem, there's no reason to believe that the number of updates required to reach a minimum happens to coincide with the number of mini-batches in your data set.

Second answer:

Generally whenever you want to optimize you use gradient descent. Gradient descent has a parameter called learning rate. In one iteration alone you can not guarantee that the gradient descent algorithm would converge to a local minima with the specified learning rate. That is the reason why you iterate again for the gradient descent to converge better.

Its also a good practice to change learning rates per epoch by observing the learning curves for better convergence.

Does every model needs several epochs? Yes

Here we set number of epochs to 40 to cause the training overfitting.

Part four: Regularization Impact¶

--> Testing with 0.0001:

Regularizers allow you to apply penalties on layer parameters or layer activity during optimization. These penalties are summed into the loss function that the network optimizes.

l1: L1 regularization effect on the neural network weight values is that it penalizes weight values that are close to 0 by making them equal to 0. Negative weight values also take a value of 0; so if a weight value is -2, under the effect of L1 regularization, it becomes 0. The general intuition with L1 regularization is that, if a weight value is close to 0 or very small, then its negligible when it comes to the overall performance of the model, therefore making it 0 does not affect the models performance and can reduce the memory capacity of the model. L1 penalizes the sum of the absolute values of the weights (|weight|)

l2: L2 regularization also penalizes weight values. For both small weight values and relatively large ones, L2 regularization transforms the values to a number close to 0, but not quite 0. l2 penalizes the sum of the square of the weights (weight)

--> Testing with dropout 0.1:

The Dropout layer randomly sets input units to 0 with a frequency of rate at each step during training time, which helps prevent overfitting. Inputs not set to 0 are scaled up by 1/(1 - rate) such that the sum over all inputs is unchanged.

dropout is a regularizer technique that reduces the odds of overfitting by dropping out neurons at random, during every epoch (or, when using a minibatch approach, during every minibatch).

Dropping out neurons happens by attaching Bernoulli variables to the neural outputs (Srivastava et al., 2014). These variables, which take the value of 1 with probability p and 0 with 1p, help reduce overfitting by making the presence of other (..) units unreliable. This way, neural networks cannot generate what Srivastava et al. call complex co-adaptations that do not generalize to unseen data.

By consequence, the occurrence of overfitting is reduced.

source: https://www.machinecurve.com/index.php/2019/12/18/how-to-use-dropout-with-keras/
